<h1>From Nicholas Cooke</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Providence October 25th 1775.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Captain Whipple returned here from his Voyage to Bermuda on Friday last.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> He had received authentick Intelligence of the Arrival of the Packet at New-York before the First Time limited for his Cruise was expired, and immediately sailed for Bermuda.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> He had light flattering Winds for several Days, and, when near the Island, met with a violent Gale, which drove him Three or Four Degrees to the Southward, and occasioned his having a long Passage. He put in at the West End of the Island, where the Inhabitants, taking him to be an armed Vessel belonging to the King, were thrown into the utmost Confusion, and the Women and Children fled into the Country. But upon
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-02-02-pb-0233">[233]</span>
shewing his Commission and Instructions were satisfied, and treated him with great Cordiality and Friendship: They informed him that, upon the Powders being removed,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> the Governor had given General Gage an Account of the Part they had taken in the Transaction, who had dispatched a Sloop of War, and a Transport of 600 Tons to take all the Provisions sent to the Island. They then lay at George Town, and treated the Islanders as Rebels. Capt. Whipple had Five of the Kings Council on board his Sloop, who all assured him that the Inhabitants were hearty Friends to the American Cause, and heartily disposed to serve it. As the Assistance they gave in the Removal of the Powder hath made them obnoxious to the Enemy, and reduced them to a disagreeable Situation, I think they ought to be treated with every Mark of Friendship. I submit to your Excellency the Propriety of your representing their Case to the Continental Congress, and recommending them to Favour.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>We are fitting out Capt. Whipple for a Cruize to the Eastward with all possible Expedition; which I hope will prove more fortunate than his last.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></p>
<p>I am, with Acknowledgment of the polite Treatment I received from you at Cambridge, and with great Respect, Sir Your humble, and most obedient Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Nichs Cooke</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. I inclose your Address to the Inhabitants of Bermuda.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0006" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0006-ptr">6</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>;

<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Draft: a draft of a letter or document in the handwriting of someone other than the author ]">Df</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Rhode Island Historical Society, Providence ]">RHi</span>: Cooke Papers.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>20 October.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0002">2</a>
	
   <p>For Abraham Whipples orders regarding the packet ship, see Cooke to GW, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0336" class="document">9</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0359" class="document">14</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0042" class="document">26</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0059" class="document">29 Sept. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0003">3</a>
	
   <p>For the removal of the gunpowder by American vessels, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0363&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-01-02-0363-fn-0001#GEWN-03-01-02-0363-fn-0001" class="document">Cooke to GW, 15 Sept. 1775, n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>For GWs response to this suggestion, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0231" class="document">GW to Cooke, 29 Oct. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>On 12 Nov. Cooke instructed Whipple to cruise in the armed sloop <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Katy</span> between Nantucket Shoals and Halifax for so long a time as you shall think proper, not exceeding six weeks and to take all vessels with soldiers, arms, ammunition, provisions, naval or warlike or other stores for the supply of the Ministerial army and navy (R.I. Revolutionary Correspondence, 13435). On 21 Nov., however, Cooke ordered Whipple to take his vessel to Philadelphia.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0215-fn-0006">6</a>
	
   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0311" class="document">Address to the Inhabitants of Bermuda, 6 Sept. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
